.com/International/wireStory?id=1444354 |title=President of West Japan Railway to Resign |agency=Associated Press |publisher=ABC News |accessdate=27 December 2005 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110629082931/http://abcnews.go.com/International/wireStory?id=1444354 |archivedate=29 June 2011 }} \n* {{cite news| date=6 August 2007| url=http://search.japantimes.co.jp/cgi-bin/nn20070806a3.html| title=JR West admits fatal crash could have been avoided| publisher=Kyodo News (reprinted by Japan Times)| accessdate=6 August 2007}}\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=laZ0b6tSYQo Seconds to Disaster Documentary (YouTube)]\n\n{{2005 railway accidents}}\n\n[[Category:Derailments in Japan]]\n[[Category:Railway accidents in 2005]]\n[[Category:2005 in Japan]]\n[[Category:Accidents and incidents involving West Japan Railway Company]]\n[[Category:April 2005 events in Asia]]\n[[Category:Rail accidents caused by a driver's error]]\n[[Category:Rail transport in Hy\u014dgo Prefecture]]\n[[Category:Heisei period]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{{More citations needed|date=April 2013 }}\n{{Infobox public transit accident\n| name                = Amagasaki derailment\n<!-- Image          -->\n| image               = Fukuchiyama joko20051.jpg\n| image_size          = \n| image_alt           = \n| caption             = Aftermath of the Amagasaki derailment\n<!-- Maps           -->\n| image_map           = \n| image_map_alt       = \n| image_map_caption   = \n| pushpin_map         = \n| alternative_map     = \n| pushpin_map_alt     = \n| pushpin_map_caption = \n| mapframe            = \n| qid                 = \n| mapframe_zoom       = \n| coordinates         = {{Coord|34|44|29.3|N|135|25|35.7|E|region:JP_scale:10000_type:event|display=inline,title}}\n<!-- Details        -->\n| date                = 25 April 2005\n| time                = 09:19 (JST)\n| location            = [[Amagasaki]], [[Hyogo Prefecture]]\n| location_dir        = \n| location_city       = \n| location_dist_km    = \n| location_dist_mi    = \n| country             = Japan\n| line                = [[Fukuchiyama Line]]\n| operator            = [[West Japan Railway Company]]\n| owner               = \n| service             = \n| type                = Derailment\n| cause               = Overspeed on curve arising from harsh penalties for lateness; retraining system\n<!-- Statistics     --> \n| bus                 = \n| trains              = 1\n| vehicles            = \n| passengers          = Approx 700\n| crew                = \n| pedestrians         = \n| deaths              = 107\n| injuries            = 562\n| damage              = \n| property            = \n<!-- Route map      -->\n| route_map           = {{Infobox rdt|map=\n{{BS|CONTg||{{RoutemapRoute|Licon=u|to Sanda and Fukuchiyama|enclosed=no}}||}}\n{{BS|BHF||{{STN|Takarazuka|JR West}}||}}\n{{BS|LSTR||||}}\n{{BS|pBHF||{{STN|Tsukaguchi|JR West}}||}}\n{{BS5|STR+l|STRq|xABZgrxl|O3=INCIDO|exSTR+r|||'''Accident occurred'''||}}\n{{BS5|STR|exKDSTa|exSTR|exSTR|||''Amagasakishijo''||}}\n{{BS5|STR|exSTR|exSTRf|exDST|||''Nagasu''||}}\n{{BS5|ABZql|eABZql|eABZql|xKRZo|STR+r||{{RoutemapRoute|Licon=l|Tokaido Line (JR Kobe Line)|enclosed=no}}||}}\n{{BS5||||exBHF|STR||''Amagasaki'' (temporary)||}}\n{{BS5||||exLSTR|BHF||{{STN|Amagasaki|JR West}}||}}\n{{BS5|||||CONTf||{{RoutemapRoute|to Osaka and Kitashinchi|Ricon=d|enclosed=no}}||}}\n}}\n| route_map_state     = collapsed\n| route_map_name      = Fukuchiyama Line (JR Takarazuka Line) route map (Takarazuka \u2013 Amagasaki, Rapid)\n<!-- Footnotes      --> \n| footnotes           = \n}}\n\nThe {{Nihongo|'''Amagasaki derailment'''|JR\u798f\u77e5\u5c71\u7dda\u8131\u7dda\u4e8b\u6545|JR Fukuchiyama-sen dassen jiko|lit. \"JR Fukuchiyama Line derailment\"}} was a fatal railway derailment which occurred on 25 April 2005 at 09:19 local time (00:19 [[UTC]]), just after the local [[rush hour]]. A seven-car [[commuter train]] came off the tracks on the [[JR West]] [[Fukuchiyama Line]] in [[Amagasaki]], Hyogo prefecture (near [[Osaka]]), just before [[Amagasaki Station (JR West)|Amagasaki Station]] on its way for D\u014dshisha-mae via the [[JR T\u014dzai Line]] and the [[Gakkentoshi Line]], and the front two carriages rammed into an [[apartment building]]. The first carriage slid into the first floor parking garage and as a result took days to remove, while the second slammed into the corner of the building, being crushed against it by the weight of the remaining carriages. Of the roughly 700 passengers (initial estimate was 580 passengers) on board at the time of the crash, 106 passengers, in addition to the driver, <!-- i.e. 107 dead in total, not 107 passengers dead --> were killed and 562 others injured. Most passengers and bystanders have said that the train appeared to have been travelling too fast. The incident was Japan's most serious since the 1963 [[Tsurumi rail accident]] in which two passenger trains collided with a derailed freight train, killing 162&nbsp;people.\n\n==Train details and crash==\n[[File:JR-W 207series(old).JPG|thumb|A 207 series EMU train similar to the one involved in the Amagasaki rail crash]]\nThe train involved was train number 5418M, a limited-stop \"Rapid\" commuter service from {{STN|Takarazuka|JR West}} to {{STN|D\u014dshisha-mae}}. It was a seven-car [[207 series]] [[electric multiple unit]] (EMU) formation consisting of a 4-car set and a 3-car set coupled together as shown below, with car 1 leading.<ref name=\"journal465\">{{cite journal| last = Nagase| first = Kazuhiko| title = \u798f\u77e5\u5c71\u7dda\u8131\u7dda\u4e8b\u6545\u306e\u554f\u984c\u3092\u8a9e\u308b|trans-title= Discussing the problems of the Fukuchiyama Line derailment| journal = Railway Journal | volume = 39| issue = 465| pages =68\u201373| publisher = Tetsud\u014d Journal | location = Japan | date = July 2005}}</ref> The train was carrying approximately 700 passengers at the time of the accident.<ref name=\"journal465\"/>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Car No. !! 1 !! 2 !! 3 !! 4  !! 5 !! 6 !! 7\n|-\n! Numbering\n| KuHa 207-17 || MoHa 207-31 || MoHa 206-17 || KuHa 206-129 || KuMoHa 207-1033 || SaHa 207-1019 || KuHa 206-1033\n|}\n\nThe front four cars derailed completely, with the first car ramming into the parking lot of the apartment building and the second car colliding into the external wall of the building becoming almost completely compacted by the third and fourth cars, which were themselves pushed from the rear by the fifth car.<ref name=\"journal465\"/>\n\n==Investigation==\n[[File:Railway Accident Investigation Report on Amagasaki derailment-English excerpt version.pdf|thumb|The investigation report of the accident.]]\nInvestigators have primarily focused on the speeding by the 23-year-old driver, later identified as Ry\u016bjir\u014d Takami (who was among the dead), as being the most likely cause of the derailment. 25 minutes before the derailment, Takami had [[signal passed at danger|run a red signal]], causing the [[automatic train stop]] (ATS) to bring the train to a halt.<ref name=\"Seconds from Disaster\">''[[Seconds From Disaster]]'' \u2013 ''Runaway Train'' \u2013 season 6, episode 7</ref> The train had also overshot the correct stopping position at an earlier stop at [[Itami Station (JR West)|Itami Station]], requiring him to back up the train, and resulting in a 90-second delay,<ref name=\"journal465\"/> about 4 minutes before the disaster.<ref name=\"Seconds from Disaster\" /> By the time the train passed [[Tsukaguchi Station (JR West)|Tsukaguchi Station]] at a speed of 120&nbsp;km/h, the delay had been reduced to 60 seconds.<ref name=\"journal465\"/>\n\nInvestigators speculate that the driver may have been trying to make up this lost time by increasing the train's speed beyond customary limits. Many reports from surviving passengers indicate that the train was traveling at a faster than normal speed. Furthermore, it is speculated that the driver may have felt stressed because he would have been punished for the two infractions. Ten months before the crash, the driver had been reprimanded for overshooting a station platform by 100 meters. In the minutes leading up to the derailment, he may have been thinking of the punishment he would have faced, and may have not been totally focused on driving.<ref name=\"Seconds from Disaster\" />\n\nThe [[West Japan Railway Company]] is very strict when it comes to punctuality,<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Nagata|first1=Takashi|last2=Rosborough|first2=Stephanie N.|last3=VanRooyen|first3=Michael J.|last4=Kozawa|first4=Shuichi|last5=Ukai|first5=Takashi|last6=Nakayama|first6=Shinichi|title=Express Railway Disaster in Amagasaki: A Review of Urban Disaster Response Capacity in Japan|journal=Prehosp Disaster Med|date=Sep\u2013Oct 2006|volume=21|issue=5|page=345|doi=10.1017/S1049023X0000399X}}</ref> and commuters often depend on near-perfect timing on the part of trains to commute to and from work on time. This is because at stations (including the derailed train's next scheduled stop at Amagasaki Station) trains meet on both sides of the same platform to allow people to transfer between rapid and local trains running on the same line. As a result, a small delay in one train can significantly cascade through the timetable for the rest of the day due to the tightness of the schedule. Immediately after the crash occurred, some of the mass media pointed to the congested schedule of the [[Fukuchiyama Line]] as an indirect factor. In fact, cumulative changes over the previous three years had reduced the leeway in the train's schedule from 71 to 28 seconds over the 15&nbsp;minutes between Takarazuka and Amagasaki stations.\n\nDrivers face financial penalties for lateness as well as being forced into harsh and humiliating retraining programs known as {{Nihongo3|\"dayshift education\"|\u65e5\u52e4\u6559\u80b2|nikkin ky\u014diku}}, which include weeding and grass-cutting duties during the day.<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.fm-world.co.uk/news/fm-industry-news/drivers-win-toilet-battle-with-japan-train-firm/ | title=Drivers win toilet battle with Japan train firm &#124; Facilitate &#124; Workplace & Facilitate Magazine}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.japantimes.co.jp/news/2005/07/23/national/1182-retraining-sessions-at-jr-west/ | title=1,182 'retraining sessions' at JR West | newspaper=The Japan Times Online | date=23 July 2005 | accessdate=2 December 2012}}</ref> The final report officially concluded that the retraining system was one probable cause of the crash.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.japantimes.co.jp/news/2007/06/29/national/jr-train-driver-faulted-in-final-report-on-crash | title=JR, train driver faulted in final report on crash | newspaper=The Japan Times Online | date=29 June 2007 | accessdate=2 December 2012}}</ref> This program consisted of severe verbal abuse, forcing the employees to repent by writing extensive reports. Also, during these times, drivers were forced to perform minor tasks, particularly involving cleaning, instead of their normal jobs. Many experts saw the process of ''nikkin kyoiku'' as a punishment and psychological torture, and not as driver retraining.<ref name=\"Seconds from Disaster\" /> The driver had also received a non-essential phone call from the general control station at the time he was rounding the bend.<ref>http://www.mlit.go.jp/jtsb/eng-rail_report/RA2007-3-1en.pdf</ref>\n\nThe [[speed limit]] on the segment of track where the derailment happened was {{Convert|70|km/h|mph|abbr=on}}. The data recorder in the rear of the train (the rear cars were new and equipped with many extra devices) later showed that the train was moving at {{Convert|116|km/h|mph|abbr=on}} at that point. Investigators ran a series of simulations and calculated that the train would derail on that curve if going any speed over {{Convert|106|km/h|mph|abbr=on}}. It has been speculated that the driver was so stressed about the inevitability of going back to ''nikkin kyoiku'' due to the prior infractions from that morning that he did not notice that the train was going too fast. When the driver did notice it, four seconds before the derailment, he used the service brake, instead of the emergency brake, presumably to avoid another infraction, since the use of the emergency brake had to be justified.<ref name=\"Seconds from Disaster\" />\n\nJapanese building codes do not regulate the distance between train lines and residential buildings due to high confidence in the engineering of the rail system. Railway lines often pass close to residential buildings in metropolitan areas.\n\n== Aftermath ==\nAmongst other things, the Ministry of Land and Transportation asked all railway companies to update their automatic stopping systems so that trains brake automatically to slow down as they approach sharp curves.\n\nIt is believed that a contributing factor in the accident was the JR West policy of schedule punctuality. As a result of this, Masataka Ide, JR West adviser who played a major role in enforcing the punctuality of the company's trains, announced that he would resign in June 2005 at the company's annual shareholder meeting, with the company's chairman and president resigning in August.\n\nThe section where the crash occurred, between Amagasaki and Takarazuka stations, was re-opened for service on 19 June 2005. The speed limits were reduced from {{convert|120|to|95|kph|abbr=on}} for the straight section and from {{convert|70|to|60|kph|abbr=on}} for the curved rail section around the accident site.\n\nAccording to the investigations carried out by the Hy\u014dgo Prefecture police, out of the 107 deaths, at least 43 (27 men, 16 women), including the driver, were in the first car, at least 45 (22 men, 23 women) were in the second car, and at least one was in the third car. This information was determined by questioning 519 of the approximately 550 injured passengers.\n\nOn 26 December 2005, Takeshi Kakiuchi officially resigned from the presidency of JR West in a move intended to take responsibility for the accident. Kakiuchi's successor was Masao Yamazaki, who had previously served as the railway's vice president, based in [[Osaka]]. While Kakiuchi's resignation came a day after [[Inaho#Accident|another serious accident]] on JR East, officials at the railway did not make any explicit connection between the recent accident and the resignation.\n[[File:Jrwest-amagasaki.png|thumb|right|As of 2020, the report for this incident still takes a prominent place on West JR's homepage. The text reads \"We will never forget the Amagasaki rail crash we caused on 25 April 2005\".]]\n\nA 2008 ''[[The Daily Yomiuri]]'' article stated that survivors of the disaster still faced physical and mental health issues.<ref>\"[https://web.archive.org/web/20080430022234/https://www.yomiuri.co.jp/dy/national/20080421TDY02309.htm '05 JR West crash victims, families still suffer effects].\" ''[[The Daily Yomiuri]]''. 21 April 2008. Archived from [https://www.yomiuri.co.jp/dy/national/20080421TDY02309.htm the original] on 30 April 2008. Retrieved 21 September 2019.</ref>\n\nOn 8 July 2009, West Japan Railway Co. President Masao Yamazaki was charged with negligence. On the same day, he announced at a press briefing in Osaka that he would resign, \"so the company can operate normally.\"<ref>\"[https://www.bloomberg.com/apps/news?pid=20601101&sid=acU1NgOk6n9c West Japan Railway Chief Yamazaki Says He Will Resign].\" ''[[Bloomberg L.P.]]''.</ref><ref>[http://search.japantimes.co.jp/cgi-bin/nn20090709a1.html JR West president indicted over crash]. ''[[The Japan Times]]'' 9 July 2009</ref>\n\nOn 11 January 2012, Yamazaki was found not guilty of professional negligence by judge Makoto Okada of the Kobe District Court, saying the accident was not sufficiently predictable to merit a finding of guilt.  The court, however, criticized JR West for faulty risk assessment of the curve where the accident happened.<ref>[[Kyodo News]], \"[http://www.japantimes.co.jp/text/nn20120111x1.html Court clears former JR chief in '05 derailment]\", ''[[The Japan Times]]'', 12 January 2012, p. 1.</ref>\n\nThe building hit by the train was demolished in 2017. As of April 2019, a memorial was built on its site and only one corner of the building was left standing.\n\n== Similar accidents ==\n\n=== Too fast around sharp curve ===\n* United Kingdom [[Salisbury rail crash]], 1906 \u2013 28 killed\n* United States [[Malbone Street Wreck]], 1918 in New York \u2013 98 killed\n* United States [[Red Arrow crash]], 1947 in Pennsylvania - 24 killed\n* Australia [[Camp Mountain train disaster]], 1947 \u2013 16 killed\n* Japan [[Hachik\u014d Line derailment]], February 1947 \u2013 184 killed\n* United Kingdom [[Sutton Coldfield rail crash|Sutton Coldfield train disaster]], 1955 \u2013 17 killed\n* United Kingdom [[Morpeth rail crash]]es, 1969, 1984, 1994 \u2013 a total of 6 killed in three separate accidents\n* United Kingdom [[Eltham Well Hall rail crash]], 1972 \u2013 6 killed\n* United States [[Cajon Pass]], 1989, 1996 - 8 killed (6 in 1989 and 2 in 1996).\n* Italy [[Piacenza derailment]], 1997 \u2013 8 killed\n* Germany [[Br\u00fchl train disaster]], 2000 \u2013 9 killed\n* Australia [[Waterfall train disaster]], 2003 \u2013 7 killed\n* Australia [[Cairns Tilt Train derailment]], 2004 \u2013 0 killed\n* Spain [[Valencia Metro derailment]], 2006 \u2013 41 killed\n* Spain [[Santiago de Compostela derailment]], 2013 \u2013 79 killed\n* United States [[December 2013 Spuyten Duyvil derailment|Spuyten Duyvil derailment]], 2013 \u2013 4 killed\n* United States [[2015 Philadelphia train derailment]] \u2013 8 killed\n* United States [[2017 Washington train derailment]] - 3 killed\n* Taiwan [[2018 Yilan train derailment]], October 2018 - 18 killed\n\n=== Failure to check speed after stop and proceed ===\n* Australia [[Glenbrook train disaster]], 1999 \u2013 7 killed\n\n== See also ==\n* [[List of rail disasters]]\n\n== Media ==\n* ''Brakeless'', a 2014 [[Peabody Award]] winning documentary film on the accident by Kyoko Miyake.<ref name=\"BRAKELESS\">[https://www.pbs.org/independentlens/films/brakeless/ \"Brakeless\"], ''pbs.org'', [[PBS]].</ref>\n* Featured on [[National Geographic]]'s show: [[Seconds from Disaster]]. (S06E05, Runaway train).,<ref>[[National Geographic]]</ref> [[Seconds From Disaster]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [[Aircraft and Railway Accidents Investigation Commission]] Official report (agency has since merged into the [[Japan Transport Safety Board]])\n** [http://www.mlit.go.jp/jtsb/eng-rail_report/RA2007-3-1en.pdf Train Derailment Accident between Tsukaguchi and Amagasaki Stations of the Fukuchiyama Line of the West Japan Railway Company (Excerpt)] ([https://www.webcitation.org/6U9B8lYSv?url=http://web.archive.org/web/20140304160950/http://www.mlit.go.jp/jtsb/eng-rail_report/RA2007-3-1en.pdf Archive]) - 22 June 2007 - English translation\n** {{in lang|ja}} {{cite web|script-title=ja:\u798f\u77e5\u5c71\u7dda\u8131\u7dda\u4e8b\u6545\u30fb\u4e8b\u6545\u8abf\u67fb\u5831\u544a\u66f8|trans-title=Fukuchiyama Line Derailment Accident Investigation Report|url=http://jtsb.mlit.go.jp/jtsb/railway/bunkatsu.html|publisher=Aircraft and Railway Accidents Investigation Commission|accessdate=21 December 2011|language=Japanese|date=1 March 2007}} - [https://web.archive.org/web/20130105225210/http://jtsb.mlit.go.jp/jtsb/railway/report/RA07-3-1.pdf First page]\n* {{cite news| date=25 April 2005| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/asia-pacific/4480031.stm| title=Japanese train crash kills dozens| publisher=BBC}}\n* {{cite news| date=26 April 2005| url=http://www.smh.com.au/news/World/Japan-begins-train-crash-investigations/2005/04/26/1114462040883.html?oneclick=true| title=Japan begins train crash investigation| work=[[Sydney Morning Herald]]}}\n* {{cite news| date=26 April 2005| url=http://www.latimes.com/news/nationworld/world/la-fg-crash26apr26,0,3988822.story?coll=la-home-world| title=Death toll rises in Japan crash| work=[[Los Angeles Times]] | first=Bruce | last=Wallace}}\n* {{cite news| date=27 April 2005| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/asia-pacific/4492267.stm| title=Japan rail crash toll tops 100| publisher=BBC}}\n* {{cite news| date=28 April 2005| title=International Herald Tribune| pages=1;8}}\n* {{cite news| date=14 May 2005| url=http://www.smh.com.au/news/World/Rail-crash-exposes-cracks-in-a-society-under-strain/2005/05/13/1115843371739.html?oneclick=true| title=Rail crash exposes cracks in a society under strain| work=Sydney Morning Herald}}\n* {{cite news| date=18 May 2005| url=http://www.trains.com/Content/Dynamic/Articles/000/000/005/931bhcvj.asp| title=Japanese executives to resign over commuter-train derailment| work=Trains News Wire| publisher=Kalmbach Publishing| accessdate=19 May 2005}} {{Dead link|date=October 2010|bot=H3llBot}}\n* {{cite news|date=26 December 2005 |url=http://abcnews.go.com/International/wireStory?id=1444354 |title=President of West Japan Railway to Resign |agency=Associated Press |publisher=ABC News |accessdate=27 December 2005 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110629082931/http://abcnews.go.com/International/wireStory?id=1444354 |archivedate=29 June 2011 }} \n* {{cite news| date=6 August 2007| url=http://search.japantimes.co.jp/cgi-bin/nn20070806a3.html| title=JR West admits fatal crash could have been avoided| publisher=Kyodo News (reprinted by Japan Times)| accessdate=6 August 2007}}\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=luZJDrTsW4Q Seconds to Disaster Documentary ( YouTube)]\n\n{{2005 railway accidents}}\n\n[[Category:Derailments in Japan]]\n[[Category:Railway accidents in 2005]]\n[[Category:2005 in Japan]]\n[[Category:Accidents and incidents involving West Japan Railway Company]]\n[[Category:April 2005 events in Asia]]\n[[Category:Rail accidents caused by a driver's error]]\n[[Category:Rail transport in Hy\u014dgo Prefecture]]\n[[Category:Heisei period]]\n", "name_user": "CRussG", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Amagasaki_derailment"}
{"title_page": "Chinpokomon", "text_new": "{{Infobox television episode\n| title        = Chinpokomon\n| series       = South Park\n| image        = SP Chinpokomon.jpeg\n| image_size   = 240px\n| caption      = The kids in class smile with [[anime]]-like expressions and then start speaking Japanese\n| season       = 3\n| episode      = 11\n| airdate      = November 3, 1999\n| production   = 310\n| writer       = Trey Parker\n| director     = [[Trey Parker]]<br>[[Eric Stough]]\n| guests       = \n| season_article = South Park (season 3)\n| episode_list = List of South Park episodes\n| prev         = [[Korn's Groovy Pirate Ghost Mystery]]\n| next         = [[Hooked on Monkey Fonics]]\n}}\n\n\"'''Chinpokomon'''\" is the eleventh episode of the [[South Park (season 3)|third season]] of the American animated television series ''[[South Park]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.imdb.com/title/tt0705912/|title=Chinpokomon|via=www.imdb.com}}</ref> It originally aired on [[Comedy Central]] in the United States on November 3, 1999, making it the 42nd episode of the series. In the episode, the kids become fascinated with the latest fad: a fictional [[Japan]]ese [[anime]] series called ''Chinpokomon'' and its related products, such as video games and collectible toys. ''Chinpokomon'' is a parody of the popular ''[[Pok\u00e9mon]]'' media franchise. \"Chinpokomon\" was written by ''South Park'' co-creator [[Trey Parker]], who also co-directed the episode together with animation director [[Eric Stough]]. The episode was nominated for an [[Emmy Award]] in 2000.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.imdb.com/event/ev0000223/2000/1/|title=Primetime Emmy Awards (2000)|website=IMDb}}</ref>\n\n==Plot==\nThe children of South Park become obsessed with an animated Japanese cartoon, ''Chinpokomon''. The cartoon features overt [[Product placement|embedded marketing]] to encourage consumption of ''Chinpokomon''-related merchandise. Unbeknownst to the parents, ''Chinpokomon'' products all contain [[Anti-Americanism|anti-American]] sentiments with the aim of [[Cultural Assimilation|converting]] American kids to [[Japanization|Japanese]] child [[Military use of children|soldiers]].\n\n[[Kyle Broflovski|Kyle]] is originally oblivious to the fad, and as its popularity increases he reluctantly attempts to keep up-to-date to avoid ridicule from his friends. Unfortunately, the merchandise lineup is so extensive that he is always one step behind. Meanwhile, the boys make plans to attend the official ''Chinpokomon'' camp, which is actually a front for a recruit training boot camp designed by the [[government of Japan|Japanese government]] to train and brainwash the kids into becoming soldiers for an upcoming attack on [[Pearl Harbor]]. As the adults start to become aware of the scheme, the Japanese distract them by telling them that Americans have \"huge penises\" compared to the Japanese, a tactic that works well against the male characters.\n\nThe parents start to suspect the nonsensical cartoon is dangerous, as \"stupidity can be worse than vulgarity and violence\" and compare it to ''[[Battle of the Network Stars]]''. Sheila Broflofski suggests it is just another harmless fad. This is juxtaposed with the truth of the fad's influence, which has turned the children into brainwashed soldiers and left [[Kenny McCormick|Kenny]] in trance-like state after an [[Denn\u014d Senshi Porygon#Strobe lights|epileptic seizure caused from playing the Chinpokomon video game]].\n\nBecoming increasingly concerned, the parents attempt to defuse the fad's popularity by trying to manufacture new fads: The \"Wild Wacky Action Bike\", an abnormal plastic [[phosphorescence|glow-in-the-dark]] bicycle contraption that cannot be steered, and \"[[Alabama]] Man\", an abusive, [[alcoholism|alcoholic]], [[Redneck (stereotype)|redneck]] action figure that comes with a bowling alley playset and a redneck wife to use as a [[Domestic violence|punching bag]]. The boys, uninterested, call both the bike and action figure \"gay\".\n\nAs the boys march through the town with [[Emperor of Japan|Emperor]] [[Hirohito]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.imdb.com/title/tt0705912/fullcredits|title=\"South Park\" Chinpokomon (TV Episode 1999) - IMDb|via=www.imdb.com}}</ref> [[President of the United States|President]] [[Bill Clinton]] will not act against the invasion as he too has fallen for the \"incredibly large penis\" trick. Finally, the parents hit upon the idea of using [[reverse psychology]], pretending to be ''Chinpokomon'' fans themselves \u2014 figuring that whatever they like their children will immediately dislike. The trick works, and all the children except Kyle instantly lose all interest. Kyle claims that if he stops liking ''Chinpokomon'' now, he will be following the crowd, so he prepares to leave in a fighter jet to bomb Pearl Harbor. A heart-felt and contradictory speech by [[Stan Marsh|Stan]] confuses him into reluctantly getting off the jet.\n\nThe group decide to avoid fads for a while, and Kenny is discovered to have been dead for some time, as evidenced when his body explodes, unleashing a large number of rats; Cartman is disgusted while Stan and Kyle laugh.\n\n==Production==\nThe ''[[wikt:\u3061\u3093\u307d|chinpo]]'' or ''chinpoko'' element in ''Chinpokomon'' is actually a vulgar [[Japanese language|Japanese]] word for \"penis\". According to the DVD commentary, the Japanese man who repeats the \"incredibly large penis\" trick is based on someone the creators met in [[Beijing]]. South Park animator Junichi Nishimura, whom Stone met in college, played the voice of the Emperor.<ref name=\"Commentary\">{{cite video | people=Trey Parker, Matt Stone|date=2003|title=South Park: The Complete Third Season|format=Audio commentary |url= http://southpark.cc.com/clips/jx04tg/creator-commentary-chinpoko-mon |medium=DVD|publisher=Comedy Central}}</ref> Saki Miata played the Japanese Woman in Live Action Commercial.\n\n==Critical reception==\nDVD Verdict described it as \"perhaps the most devastating parody of the seemingly endless pop culture craziness of forced Japan fads\", adding: \"Beginning with the title and moving through awkward, amateur anime, video games that cause seizures, and parental confusion over what their kids see in the little crappy toys, the episode smacks of too much truth and contains many moments of ultra-high comedy...This particular episode is why South Park is sometimes begrudgingly called genius, even amongst those who consider it a peek inside the Antichrist's subconscious. It proves that, on occasion, Parker can take the envelope, fill it full of outrageous sentiments and blatant stereotyping, mix in a whole lot of social realities, and filter it through his own sense of tasteless humor and end up with yet another brilliant installment of his show.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dvdverdict.com/reviews/southparkseason3.php|title=DVD Verdict Review - South Park: The Complete Third Season|work=DVD Verdict|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140901020210/http://www.dvdverdict.com/reviews/southparkseason3.php|archivedate=2014-09-01}}</ref>\n\nElderGeek described the episode as \"a very ironic take on children\u2019s trends and how debilitating they can be\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://elder-geek.com/2010/09/top-10-geekiest-south-park-episodes/|title=Top 10 Geekiest South Park Episodes|work=Elder-Geek.com}}</ref> PixelatedPop ranked the episode 23rd in a top 25 greatest episodes list in 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pixelatedpop.com/article/20120927/top-25-south-park-episodes|title=Top 25 South Park Episodes|work=pixelatedpop.com}}</ref> ScreenJunkies wrote \"The blindness of parents, the zombie-like children following a fad, and the irrational paranoia of Americans who fear the Japanese simply because they make the occasional incomprehensible TV show were all parodied to perfection\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.screenjunkies.com/tv/tv-news/12-best-south-park-political-parodies/|title=12 Best 'South Park' Political Parodies|work=Screen Junkies}}</ref> IGN said \"''Chinpokomon'' was a great rip on the whole Pokemon craze with a lot of crude jokes about Asian male anatomy\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://au.ign.com/articles/2003/12/17/south-park-the-complete-third-season|title=South Park: The Complete Third Season|work=IGN}}</ref>\n\nThe AV Club noted that this episode was the first instance of the South Park ''fad episode'', in which \"Characters briefly latch onto something fleetingly popular and often inherently stupid\u2014which is then obsessed about to the detriment of their relationships (or, occasionally, the safety of the entire town)\u2014then, inevitably, they realize that the object of their obsession is dumb and drop it forever.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.avclub.com/tvclub/south-park-creme-fraiche-47742|title=Review: South Park: \"Cr\u00e9me Fraiche\" \u00b7 TV Club  \u00b7 The A.V. Club|work=avclub.com}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikiquote}}\n* [http://www.southparkstudios.com/full-episodes/s03e10-chinpoko-mon Chinpoko Mon] Full episode at South Park Studios\n* [http://www.southparkstudios.com/guide/episodes/s03e10-chinpokomon Chinpoko Mon] Episode guide at South Park Studios\n* [https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0705912/ Chinpokomon] IMDB Episode Page\n* {{Tv.com episode|2456}}\n\n{{South Park episodes|3}}\n\n[[Category:1999 American television episodes]]\n[[Category:Anime-influenced Western animation]]\n[[Category:Television episodes set in Japan]]\n[[Category:Works based on Pok\u00e9mon]]\n[[Category:South Park (season 3) episodes]]\n[[Category:Television episodes about advertising]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox television episode\n| title        = Chinpokomon\n| series       = South Park\n| image        = SP Chinpokomon.jpeg\n| image_size   = 240px\n| caption      = The kids in class smile with [[anime]]-like expressions and then start speaking Japanese\n| season       = 3\n| episode      = 11\n| airdate      = November 3, 1999\n| production   = 310\n| writer       = Trey Parker\n| director     = [[Trey Parker]]<br>[[Eric Stough]]\n| guests       = \n| season_article = South Park (season 3)\n| episode_list = List of South Park episodes\n| season_list  =\n| prev         = [[Korn's Groovy Pirate Ghost Mystery]]\n| next         = [[Hooked on Monkey Fonics]]\n}}\n\n\"'''Chinpokomon'''\" is the eleventh episode of the [[South Park (season 3)|third season]] of the American animated television series ''[[South Park]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.imdb.com/title/tt0705912/|title=Chinpokomon|via=www.imdb.com}}</ref> It originally aired on [[Comedy Central]] in the United States on November 3, 1999, making it the 42nd episode of the series. In the episode, the kids become fascinated with the latest fad: a fictional [[Japan]]ese [[anime]] series called ''Chinpokomon'' and its related products, such as video games and collectible toys. ''Chinpokomon'' is a parody of the popular ''[[Pok\u00e9mon]]'' media franchise. \"Chinpokomon\" was written by ''South Park'' co-creator [[Trey Parker]], who also co-directed the episode together with animation director [[Eric Stough]]. The episode was nominated for an [[Emmy Award]] in 2000.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.imdb.com/event/ev0000223/2000/1/|title=Primetime Emmy Awards (2000)|website=IMDb}}</ref>\n\n==Plot==\nThe children of South Park become obsessed with an animated Japanese cartoon, ''Chinpokomon''. The cartoon features overt [[Product placement|embedded marketing]] to encourage consumption of ''Chinpokomon''-related merchandise. Unbeknownst to the parents, ''Chinpokomon'' products all contain [[Anti-Americanism|anti-American]] sentiments with the aim of [[Cultural Assimilation|converting]] American kids to [[Japanization|Japanese]] child [[Military use of children|soldiers]].\n\n[[Kyle Broflovski|Kyle]] is originally oblivious to the fad, and as its popularity increases he reluctantly attempts to keep up-to-date to avoid ridicule from his friends. Unfortunately, the merchandise lineup is so extensive that he is always one step behind. Meanwhile, the boys make plans to attend the official ''Chinpokomon'' camp, which is actually a front for a recruit training boot camp designed by the [[government of Japan|Japanese government]] to train and brainwash the kids into becoming soldiers for an upcoming attack on [[Pearl Harbor]]. As the adults start to become aware of the scheme, the Japanese distract them by telling them that Americans have \"huge penises\" compared to the Japanese, a tactic that works well against the male characters.\n\nThe parents start to suspect the nonsensical cartoon is dangerous, as \"stupidity can be worse than vulgarity and violence\" and compare it to ''[[Battle of the Network Stars]]''. Sheila Broflofski suggests it is just another harmless fad. This is juxtaposed with the truth of the fad's influence, which has turned the children into brainwashed soldiers and left [[Kenny McCormick|Kenny]] in trance-like state after an [[Denn\u014d Senshi Porygon#Strobe lights|epileptic seizure caused from playing the Chinpokomon video game]].\n\nBecoming increasingly concerned, the parents attempt to defuse the fad's popularity by trying to manufacture new fads: The \"Wild Wacky Action Bike\", an abnormal plastic [[phosphorescence|glow-in-the-dark]] bicycle contraption that cannot be steered, and \"[[Alabama]] Man\", an abusive, [[alcoholism|alcoholic]], [[Redneck (stereotype)|redneck]] action figure that comes with a bowling alley playset and a redneck wife to use as a [[Domestic violence|punching bag]]. The boys, uninterested, call both the bike and action figure \"gay\".\n\nAs the boys march through the town with [[Emperor of Japan|Emperor]] [[Hirohito]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.imdb.com/title/tt0705912/fullcredits|title=\"South Park\" Chinpokomon (TV Episode 1999) - IMDb|via=www.imdb.com}}</ref> [[President of the United States|President]] [[Bill Clinton]] will not act against the invasion as he too has fallen for the \"incredibly large penis\" trick. Finally, the parents hit upon the idea of using [[reverse psychology]], pretending to be ''Chinpokomon'' fans themselves \u2014 figuring that whatever they like their children will immediately dislike. The trick works, and all the children except Kyle instantly lose all interest. Kyle claims that if he stops liking ''Chinpokomon'' now, he will be following the crowd, so he prepares to leave in a fighter jet to bomb Pearl Harbor. A heart-felt and contradictory speech by [[Stan Marsh|Stan]] confuses him into reluctantly getting off the jet.\n\nThe group decide to avoid fads for a while, and Kenny is discovered to have been dead for some time, as evidenced when his body explodes, unleashing a large number of rats; Cartman is disgusted while Stan and Kyle laugh.\n\n==Production==\nThe ''[[wikt:\u3061\u3093\u307d|chinpo]]'' or ''chinpoko'' element in ''Chinpokomon'' is actually a vulgar [[Japanese language|Japanese]] word for \"penis\". According to the DVD commentary, the Japanese man who repeats the \"incredibly large penis\" trick is based on someone the creators met in [[Beijing]]. South Park animator Junichi Nishimura, whom Stone met in college, played the voice of the Emperor.<ref name=\"Commentary\">{{cite video | people=Trey Parker, Matt Stone|date=2003|title=South Park: The Complete Third Season|format=Audio commentary |url= http://southpark.cc.com/clips/jx04tg/creator-commentary-chinpoko-mon |medium=DVD|publisher=Comedy Central}}</ref> Saki Miata played the Japanese Woman in Live Action Commercial.\n\n==Critical reception==\nDVD Verdict described it as \"perhaps the most devastating parody of the seemingly endless pop culture craziness of forced Japan fads\", adding: \"Beginning with the title and moving through awkward, amateur anime, video games that cause seizures, and parental confusion over what their kids see in the little crappy toys, the episode smacks of too much truth and contains many moments of ultra-high comedy...This particular episode is why South Park is sometimes begrudgingly called genius, even amongst those who consider it a peek inside the Antichrist's subconscious. It proves that, on occasion, Parker can take the envelope, fill it full of outrageous sentiments and blatant stereotyping, mix in a whole lot of social realities, and filter it through his own sense of tasteless humor and end up with yet another brilliant installment of his show.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dvdverdict.com/reviews/southparkseason3.php|title=DVD Verdict Review - South Park: The Complete Third Season|work=DVD Verdict|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140901020210/http://www.dvdverdict.com/reviews/southparkseason3.php|archivedate=2014-09-01}}</ref>\n\nElderGeek described the episode as \"a very ironic take on children\u2019s trends and how debilitating they can be\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://elder-geek.com/2010/09/top-10-geekiest-south-park-episodes/|title=Top 10 Geekiest South Park Episodes|work=Elder-Geek.com}}</ref> PixelatedPop ranked the episode 23rd in a top 25 greatest episodes list in 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pixelatedpop.com/article/20120927/top-25-south-park-episodes|title=Top 25 South Park Episodes|work=pixelatedpop.com}}</ref> ScreenJunkies wrote \"The blindness of parents, the zombie-like children following a fad, and the irrational paranoia of Americans who fear the Japanese simply because they make the occasional incomprehensible TV show were all parodied to perfection\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.screenjunkies.com/tv/tv-news/12-best-south-park-political-parodies/|title=12 Best 'South Park' Political Parodies|work=Screen Junkies}}</ref> IGN said \"''Chinpokomon'' was a great rip on the whole Pokemon craze with a lot of crude jokes about Asian male anatomy\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://au.ign.com/articles/2003/12/17/south-park-the-complete-third-season|title=South Park: The Complete Third Season|work=IGN}}</ref>\n\nThe AV Club noted that this episode was the first instance of the South Park ''fad episode'', in which \"Characters briefly latch onto something fleetingly popular and often inherently stupid\u2014which is then obsessed about to the detriment of their relationships (or, occasionally, the safety of the entire town)\u2014then, inevitably, they realize that the object of their obsession is dumb and drop it forever.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.avclub.com/tvclub/south-park-creme-fraiche-47742|title=Review: South Park: \"Cr\u00e9me Fraiche\" \u00b7 TV Club  \u00b7 The A.V. Club|work=avclub.com}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikiquote}}\n* [http://www.southparkstudios.com/full-episodes/s03e10-chinpoko-mon Chinpoko Mon] Full episode at South Park Studios\n* [http://www.southparkstudios.com/guide/episodes/s03e10-chinpokomon Chinpoko Mon] Episode guide at South Park Studios\n* [https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0705912/ Chinpokomon] IMDB Episode Page\n* {{Tv.com episode|2456}}\n\n{{South Park episodes|3}}\n\n[[Category:1999 American television episodes]]\n[[Category:Anime-influenced Western animation]]\n[[Category:Television episodes set in Japan]]\n[[Category:Works based on Pok\u00e9mon]]\n[[Category:South Park (season 3) episodes]]\n[[Category:Television episodes about advertising]]\n", "name_user": "Gonnym", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:clean up", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chinpokomon"}
